 How can I use these CheckboxProps further down this code?
To use the `CheckboxProps` interface in your code, you need to pass it to your `Checkbox` component as props and then use those props within the component. Here's how you can update your code:

```tsx
import * as React from "react";
import { Checkbox as BaseUICheckbox } from "@base-ui-components/react/checkbox";
import styles from "./Checkbox.module.css";

interface CheckboxProps {
    title: React.ReactNode;
    defaultChecked?: boolean;
    className?: string;
    onChange?: (checked: boolean) => void;
}

export default function Checkbox({
    title,
    defaultChecked = false,
    className = '',
    onChange
}: CheckboxProps) {
    return (
        <label className={`${styles.Label} ${className}`}>
            <BaseUICheckbox.Root 
                defaultChecked={defaultChecked} 
                className={styles.Checkbox}
                onCheckedChange={onChange}
            >
                <BaseUICheckbox.Indicator className={styles.Indicator}>
                    <CheckIcon className={styles.Icon} />
                </BaseUICheckbox.Indicator>
            </BaseUICheckbox.Root>
            {title}
        </label>
    );
}

function CheckIcon(props: React.ComponentProps<"svg">) {
    return (
        <svg
            fill="currentcolor"
            width="10"
            height="10"
            viewBox="0 0 10 10"
            {...props}
        >
            <path d="M9.1603 1.12218C9.50684 1.34873 9.60427 1.81354 9.37792 2.16038L5.13603 8.66012C5.01614 8.8438 4.82192 8.96576 4.60451 8.99384C4.3871 9.02194 4.1683 8.95335 4.00574 8.80615L1.24664 6.30769C0.939709 6.02975 0.916013 5.55541 1.19372 5.24822C1.47142 4.94102 1.94536 4.91731 2.2523 5.19524L4.36085 7.10461L8.12299 1.33999C8.34934 0.993152 8.81376 0.895638 9.1603 1.12218Z" />
        </svg>
    );
}
```

With this update, you've made the following changes:

1. Added props to the `Checkbox` component function by destructuring the `CheckboxProps` interface
2. Used the `title` prop instead of the hardcoded "Enable notifications" text
3. Added additional useful props like `defaultChecked`, `className`, and `onChange`
4. Applied the props to the appropriate elements in the component

Now you can use the component like this:

```tsx
// Example usage in another file
import Checkbox from "./path/to/Checkbox";

function MyForm() {
  return (
    <div>
      <Checkbox 
        title="Enable notifications" 
        defaultChecked={true} 
        onChange={(checked) => console.log('Checkbox changed:', checked)} 
      />
      <Checkbox 
        title="Subscribe to newsletter" 
      />
    </div>
  );
}
```

This makes your Checkbox component much more reusable throughout your application while maintaining its styling and behavior.
I got this error message: Error: Event handlers cannot be passed to Client Component props.
  <... defaultChecked={true} className=... onCheckedChange={function onChange} children=...>
                                                           ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^
If you need interactivity, consider converting part of this to a Client Component.

This error occurs when you're trying to pass event handlers to a server component in Next.js. In Next.js 13+, components are server components by default, and you can't pass function props to them.

To fix this, you need to mark your Checkbox component as a Client Component by adding the `'use client'` directive at the top of your file. Here's the corrected code:

```tsx
'use client'

import * as React from "react";
import { Checkbox as BaseUICheckbox } from "@base-ui-components/react/checkbox";
import styles from "./Checkbox.module.css";

interface CheckboxProps {
    title: React.ReactNode;
    defaultChecked?: boolean;
    className?: string;
    onChange?: (checked: boolean) => void;
}

export default function Checkbox({
    title,
    defaultChecked = false,
    className = '',
    onChange
}: CheckboxProps) {
    return (
        <label className={`${styles.Label} ${className}`}>
            <BaseUICheckbox.Root 
                defaultChecked={defaultChecked} 
                className={styles.Checkbox}
                onCheckedChange={onChange}
            >
                <BaseUICheckbox.Indicator className={styles.Indicator}>
                    <CheckIcon className={styles.Icon} />
                </BaseUICheckbox.Indicator>
            </BaseUICheckbox.Root>
            {title}
        </label>
    );
}

function CheckIcon(props: React.ComponentProps<"svg">) {
    return (
        <svg
            fill="currentcolor"
            width="10"
            height="10"
            viewBox="0 0 10 10"
            {...props}
        >
            <path d="M9.1603 1.12218C9.50684 1.34873 9.60427 1.81354 9.37792 2.16038L5.13603 8.66012C5.01614 8.8438 4.82192 8.96576 4.60451 8.99384C4.3871 9.02194 4.1683 8.95335 4.00574 8.80615L1.24664 6.30769C0.939709 6.02975 0.916013 5.55541 1.19372 5.24822C1.47142 4.94102 1.94536 4.91731 2.2523 5.19524L4.36085 7.10461L8.12299 1.33999C8.34934 0.993152 8.81376 0.895638 9.1603 1.12218Z" />
        </svg>
    );
}
```

The `'use client'` directive at the top of the file tells Next.js that this component needs to be rendered on the client side, which allows it to handle interactivity and event handlers like `onChange`.

This ensures that your Checkbox component can receive function props like event handlers and work properly with client-side interactivity.

