# Fixing CSS Variables Issue in Next.js

It looks like you're having an issue with CSS variables not being properly applied in your Checkbox component. This is likely because the theme variables defined in `theme.css` aren't being imported into your component's scope.

## Solution: Import the Theme CSS

You need to ensure that your `theme.css` file is properly imported into your application. Here are a few ways to fix this:

### Option 1: Import in the Component

Add 'use client' to your Checkbox component and import the theme CSS file directly:

```tsx
'use client'

import * as React from "react";
import { Checkbox as BaseUICheckbox } from "@base-ui-components/react/checkbox";
import styles from "./Checkbox.module.css";
import '@/app/components/theme.css'; // Import the theme CSS

interface CheckboxProps {
    title: React.ReactNode;
    defaultChecked?: boolean;
    className?: string;
    onChange?: (checked: boolean) => void;
}

export default function Checkbox({
    title,
    defaultChecked = false,
    className = "",
    onChange,
}: CheckboxProps) {
    return (
        <label className={`${styles.Label} ${className}`}>
            <BaseUICheckbox.Root
                defaultChecked={defaultChecked}
                className={styles.Checkbox}
                onCheckedChange={onChange}
            >
                <BaseUICheckbox.Indicator className={styles.Indicator}>
                    <CheckIcon className={styles.Icon} />
                </BaseUICheckbox.Indicator>
            </BaseUICheckbox.Root>
            {title}
        </label>
    );
}

// ... rest of your component
```

### Option 2: Import in the Root Layout

The better approach is to import your theme CSS once in your root layout file. In Next.js, this would typically be in your `app/layout.tsx` file:

```tsx
// app/layout.tsx
import './components/theme.css';

export default function RootLayout({
  children,
}: {
  children: React.ReactNode
}) {
  return (
    <html lang="en">
      <body>{children}</body>
    </html>
  )
}
```

This ensures the theme variables are available throughout your entire application.

### Option 3: Move Variables to Global CSS

Another approach is to move your theme variables to the global CSS file that Next.js automatically includes:

1. Add the variables to `app/globals.css` (or create it if it doesn't exist)
2. Import this file in your root layout

```css
/* globals.css */
:root {
    --color-blue: oklch(45% 50% 264);
    --color-red: oklch(50% 55% 31);
    /* rest of your variables */
}

/* Add your other global styles here */
```

## Alternative: Inline the Variables

If the above solutions don't work for some reason, you could directly include the variables in your component's CSS module:

```css
/* Checkbox.module.css */
.Label {
